stories: This paper seeks to establish a categorization of electronic lexicographic resources that are multilingual and plurilingual, thereby facilitating the development of a typological framework for lexicographical tools, such as dictionaries, distinct from platforms and websites, based on quantitative and qualitative criteria. Furthermore, this classification aims to differentiate between multilingual and plurilingual resources according to their level of prototyping. In addition to providing a comprehensive overview of these resources, this paper proposes parameters and typological frameworks to define and distinguish various electronic resources, including multilingual dictionaries and portals, while also examining and challenging the boundaries of the field of study in multilingual and plurilingual lexicography.

This research aims to develop a systematic classification of multilingual and plurilingual electronic lexicographic resources, providing a foundation for a typological framework that distinguishes lexicographic tools, such as dictionaries, from platforms and websites, based on both quantitative and qualitative metrics. The proposed categorization also seeks to draw a clear distinction between multilingual and plurilingual resources based on their prototyping level. Moreover, this study offers a comprehensive survey of these resources, introducing parameters and typological frameworks to define and differentiate various electronic resources, including multilingual dictionaries and portals, while exploring and redefining the boundaries of multilingual and plurilingual lexicography.
